Title: John Moore watches William Focher die after being shot by police, Los Angeles, 1935
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 1147-- John G. Moore, William Focher-- Focher dying, Shooting of Focher, 9/11/35|~|Handwritten on negative: William Focher, John G. Moore
Description.note: Shortly after an altercation with wrestling promoter Lou Daro 35-year-old William Focher was shot by police officers after they had confused him for a bandit. After several hours of being treated at the hospital he died.|~|Similar photograph appears with the article, "Error Death to be Aired," Los Angeles Times, 12 July 1935: A1.|~|A few men can be seen standing around William as he looks up from a bed with his mouth open, a blood pressure cuff rapped around one tattooed arm. The time the picture was taken is not given, but it is assumed to be sometime between Focher's admission to the hospital and his death. His friend, John G. Moore turns his face to look at him. A female's arm/hand can be seen touching the bed as well. One man smokes while watching while another with a hat watches in front of Focher.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.

Description.note: L-R- William R. Sanderson, Robert C. Powers, and P.H. Milot talking in front of "'Old Salts', 'New Salts'" Poster. Sanderson and Milot are presumably distinguished Navy Officers judging from their stripes/symbols on their uniforms while Robert C. Powers could be "new salt" or new sailor. The American Flag is in the background as well as a map of the United States along with other pictures.

Title: Dorothy E. Bunnell holding redwood key presented to FDR by California Redwood Association, San Diego, 1935
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative: Miss Dorothy E. Bunnell|~|Text from negative sleeve: 2478 - Miss Dorothy E. Bunnell, Redwood Key Presented to President 10/2/35, [stamped:] Oct 22 1935.
Description.note: Miss Dorothy E. Bunnell holding a key made of California redwood. The key is carved with the name and logo of the Better Housing Program and the initials "FDR." This photograph may have been taken when President Franklin D. Roosevelt was gifted with a redwood key by the California Redwood Association at the California Pacific International Exposition in San Diego, California on October 2, 1935.|~|Related to the article, "Art Shown in Gift to President," Los Angeles Times, 2 Oct. 1935: 6.
